# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dc-connector
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:dc-connector/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:dc-connector/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:dc-connector/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] In the United States and Canada, the **Amateur Radio Emergency Service** (**ARES**) is a corps of trained amateur radio operator volunteers organized to assist in public service and emergency communications.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] It is organized and sponsored by the American Radio Relay League (ARRL) and the Radio Amateurs of Canada (RAC).
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Communication failures have been a defining part of natural disasters and even some human-generated events.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Amateur radio provides a means of communication "when all else fails".
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Amateur radio operators belonging to ARES (and its predecessor, the Amateur Radio Emergency Corps) have responded to local and regional disasters since the 1930s, including the attacks of September 11, 2001, and the category 5 storms Hurricane Katrina, Hurricane Michael, and the Joplin tornado.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] During the Katrina event, more than one thousand ARES volunteers assisted in the aftermath and provided communications for the American Red Cross, The Salvation Army, and other individuals related to the relief effort.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] After Katrina Hancock County, Mississippi, had lost all contact with the outside world, except through ARES operators who served as 911 dispatchers and message relayers.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] ARES has deployed for a variety of other emergencies and disasters, including the 2003 North America blackout.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] The blackout covered a wide geographical area of North America.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] In the United States its scope included Cleveland, Detroit, and New York City.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Landline telephones and cell phone systems were overloaded and amateur ability to operate off the grid was put to the test.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] On Long Island in New York many pieces of health and welfare traffic were passed on VHF and HF nets.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Because some television and radio stations had gone off the air amateurs helped fill the lack of information.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] This was not the first time that amateur radio operators assisted during a blackout in New York City.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] On a warm evening of July 13, 1977, effects from a lightning caused a power outage across the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Radio operators started communication nets on simplex and on a repeater located in the Chrysler Building.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] ARES groups are volunteer amateur radio operators who come together for the common purpose of providing emergency and/or auxiliary communications service to public safety and public service organizations.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Most individual ARES units are autonomous and operate locally.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Although the Amateur Radio Emergency Service is a program (and trademark) of the American Radio Relay League (ARRL) in the U.S., the structure is more supportive than directive in nature, providing mostly for mutual aid in the event of large-scale emergencies.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] As long as local units are operating in the best interests of Amateur Radio in general and the ARRL in particular, intervention from the national organization is minimal.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] The government expresses little governance of ARES (other than the FCC regulations - 47 CFR Part 97 - which regulate all of Amateur Radio) and local authorities only passively regulate ARES groups by way of formal understandings.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] ARES groups are generally organized by city or county and are made up of volunteers from the local area.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] The only requirements to join ARES are a willingness to serve and a valid amateur radio license.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Groups are organized locally by the person holding the position of *Emergency Coordinator* (EC).
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] The EC maintains full responsibility for organizing the local groups and serving as their leader during operations.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] The EC is an ARRL or RAC member, and is generally the point of contact for those wishing to perform Emergency Communications in their local area.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Some members may be appointed as Official Emergency Stations and are trained to serve specific duties such as being a net controller during emergencies.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] The next higher level of coordination is the optional District Emergency Coordinator (DEC).
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] This person coordinates the operation of several local county or city ARES groups and reports to the Section Emergency Coordinator in those sections where the span of control would otherwise be too large.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] A DEC may have one or more Assistant District Emergency Coordinators serving them.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Leading the structure is the Section Emergency Coordinator, or SEC.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] This person is appointed by the elected Section Manager and is responsible for emergency communications in their section.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] An SEC may have one or more Assistant SECs serving to assist them.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] In the U.S., a Section is one of 71 geographic administrative areas of the ARRL.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] It is either a state or in more densely populated areas of the U.S., a portion of a state.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] As is the case in the U.S., each Section is managed by an elected Section Manager.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] In Canada, the ARES logo is a registered trademark of the Radio Amateurs of Canada Inc.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Often these memorandums illustrate a common and united sense of purpose between ARES and another organization.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] However, Memorandums of Understanding with the American Red Cross, the National Weather Service, the Salvation Army, and others lay out the general guidelines for organization and coordination between agencies in times of emergency.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] ARES of the Radio Amateurs of Canada have MOUs with the Canadian Red Cross Society and PERCS, the British Columbia Provincial Emergency Radio Communication Service.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Frequently, members of local ARES groups in the U.S. are registered with local government Emergency Management agencies to permit operations under the RACES rules, if ever needed.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] This allows continuation of operation during times of declared emergency when normal amateur operations might be prohibited.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Today, ARES has operators and officials at local, county, and state levels, and most potential RACES operations are generally integrated within ARES organizations.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Amateur Radio emergency communications groups have decided, for one reason or another, not to affiliate with the ARRL.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Some such groups in Canada have elected not to offer their services under the Radio Amateurs of Canada (RAC) banner.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] However, their essential purpose remains the same and, in times of need, they often work side-by-side with ARES groups.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Radio clubs independent of the ARRL or the RAC and ARES also participate in emergency communications activities in some areas.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] Many ARES operators are also part of storm spotter networks, e.g., Skywarn (a program organized by the U.S.
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] National Weather Service) and Canwarn (coordinated by Environment Canada).
[src:dc-connector/amateur-radio-emergency-service] In many cases, the ARES Emergency Coordinator for a county coordinates all local Amateur Radio emergency and disaster communications activity.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines and American Eagle operate out of ten hubs, anchored by Dallas Fort Worth International Airport (DFW), the airline's largest.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Charlotte Douglas International Airport (CLT) follows as the second-largest hub, serving as a primary gateway for Southeast and transatlantic travel.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline serves more than 200 million passengers annually, and averages more than 500,000 daily.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of 2024, the company employs 103,440 staff members.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The earliest predecessor company of American Airlines to commence operations was Robertson Aircraft Corporation, which began mail flights on April 15, 1926.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines was started in 1930 as a union of more than eighty small airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The two organizations from which American Airlines originated were Robertson Aircraft Corporation and Colonial Air Transport.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The former was first created in Missouri in 1921, with both being merged in 1929 into holding company The Aviation Corporation.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This, in turn, was made in 1930 into an operating company and rebranded as **American Airways**.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1934, when new laws and attrition of mail contracts forced many airlines to reorganize, the corporation redid its routes into a connected system and was renamed American Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline fully developed its international business between 1970 and 2000.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] It purchased Trans World Airlines in 2001.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American had a direct role in the development of the Douglas DC-3, which resulted from a marathon telephone call from American Airlines CEO C.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Smith to Douglas Aircraft Company founder Donald Wills Douglas Sr., when Smith persuaded a reluctant Douglas to design a sleeper aircraft based on the DC-2 to replace American's Curtiss Condor II biplanes.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] (The existing DC-2's cabin was 66 inches (1.7 m) wide, too narrow for side-by-side berths.) Douglas agreed to proceed with development only after Smith informed him of American Airline's intention to purchase 20 aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The prototype DST (Douglas Sleeper Transport) first flew on December 17, 1935, the 32nd anniversary of the Wright Brothers' flight at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Its cabin was 92 in (2.3 m) wide, and a version with 21 seats instead of the 14–16 sleeping berths of the DST was given the designation DC-3.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] There was no prototype DC-3; the first DC-3 built followed seven DSTs off the production line and was delivered to American Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines inaugurated passenger service on June 26, 1936, with simultaneous flights from Newark, New Jersey, and Chicago, Illinois.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American also had a direct role in the development of the DC-10, which resulted from a specification from American Airlines to manufacturers in 1966 to offer a widebody aircraft that was smaller than the Boeing 747, but capable of flying similar long-range routes from airports with shorter runways.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] McDonnell Douglas responded with the DC-10 trijet shortly after the two companies' merger.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On February 19, 1968, the president of American Airlines, George A.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] McDonnell of McDonnell Douglas announced American's intention to acquire the DC-10.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines ordered 25 DC-10s in its first order.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The DC-10 made its first flight on August 29, 1970, and received its type certificate from the FAA on July 29, 1971.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On August 5, 1971, the DC-10 entered commercial service with American Airlines on a round-trip flight between Los Angeles and Chicago.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 2011, due to a downturn in the airline industry, American Airlines' parent company, the AMR Corporation, filed for bankruptcy protection.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 2013, American Airlines merged with US Airways but kept the American Airlines name, as it was the better-recognized brand internationally; the combination of the two airlines resulted in the creation of the largest airline in the United States, and ultimately the world.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In December 2023, the company was added to the Dow Jones Sustainability World Index, and was named to the index for a second consecutive year in December 2024.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Eagle is the brand for regional airline flights operated for American Airlines, encompassing flights by wholly owned affiliates Envoy Air, PSA Airlines, and Piedmont Airlines, as well as third-party carriers Republic Airways and SkyWest Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] These regional carriers serve smaller markets, facilitating connections to American Airlines hubs, and supporting operations in mainline markets.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] All American Eagle carriers share similar logos, uniforms, and aircraft paint schemes as American Airlines’ mainline operations.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 2023, 46 million passengers flew on American Eagle regional flights, with about 45% connecting to or from mainline flights.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] These flights operate under capacity purchase agreements with both third-party and wholly owned regional carriers, controlling all aspects of marketing, scheduling, ticketing, pricing, and seat inventories.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines pays fixed fees for operating specified aircraft and covering certain variable costs, such as fuel, landing fees, and insurance.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines has established three joint ventures with fellow Oneworld alliance members, expanding beyond basic codesharing to include coordinated route planning, scheduling, and revenue sharing on jointly operated routes.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The Atlantic Joint Business covers transatlantic flights with Aer Lingus, British Airways, Finnair and Iberia.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The Pacific Joint Business encompasses transpacific flights with Japan Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] A joint venture with Qantas covers routes between the United States, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of June 2026, the American Airlines fleet consists of 1,030 mainline aircraft, making it the second largest commercial airline fleet in the world.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The fleet consists of Airbus and Boeing narrow-body aircraft, and Boeing wide-body aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American exclusively ordered Boeing aircraft throughout the 2000s until July 20, 2011, when American announced the largest combined aircraft order in history for 260 Airbus A320 family and 200 Boeing 737 aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of October 2025, American has 301 Airbus and Boeing aircraft on order along with 20 orders and 40 options for Boom Overture supersonic aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The average age of the American mainline fleet is 14.2 years as of February 2026.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of 2024, American Airlines has four maintenance bases: Tulsa International Airport, Pittsburgh International Airport, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport, and Charlotte Douglas International Airport.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Flagship First is American's international and transcontinental first class product.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] It is offered only on Boeing 777-300ERs and select Airbus A321s, which American designates "A321T".
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The seats are fully lie-flat and offer direct aisle access with only one on each side of the aisle in each row.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As with the airline's other premium cabins, Flagship First offers wider food and beverage options, larger seats, and lounge access at certain airports.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American offers domestic Flagship First service on transcontinental routes between New York–JFK and Los Angeles, New York–JFK and San Francisco, New York-JFK and Santa Ana, Boston and Los Angeles, and Miami and Los Angeles, as well as on the standard domestic route between New York-JFK and Boston.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline will debut new Flagship Suite premium seats and a revamped aircraft interior for its long-haul fleet with fresh deliveries of its Airbus A321XLR and Boeing 787-9 aircraft, beginning in 2024.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Flagship Business is American's international and transcontinental business class product.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] It is offered on all Boeing 777-200ERs, Boeing 777-300ERs, Boeing 787-8s, and Boeing 787-9s, as well as select Airbus A321s.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] All Flagship Business seats are fully lie-flat.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The amenities in Flagship Business include complimentary alcoholic/non-alcoholic beverages, multi-course meals, and lounge access.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] First Class is the highest class of service on domestically configured aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] When such aircraft are used on international services this cabin is branded as business class.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Seats range from 19–21 inches (48–53 cm) in width and have 37–42 inches (94–107 cm) of pitch.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Dining options include complimentary alcoholic and non-alcoholic beverages on all flights as well as standard economy snack offerings, enhanced snack basket selections on flights over 500 miles (800 km), and meals on flights 900 miles (1,400 km) or longer.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Premium Economy is American's economy plus product.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The cabin debuted on the airline's Boeing 787-9s in late 2016 and is also available on Boeing 777-200s and -300s, and Boeing 787-8s.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Premium Economy seats are wider than seats in the main cabin (American's economy cabin) and provide more amenities: Premium Economy customers get two free checked bags, priority boarding, and enhanced food and drink service, including free alcohol.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This product made American Airlines the first U.S. carrier to offer a four-cabin aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Main Cabin (economy class) is American's economy product found on all mainline and regional aircraft in its fleet.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American markets several rows within the main cabin immediately behind Main Cabin Extra as "Main Cabin Preferred", which requires an extra charge to select for those without status.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Main Cabin Extra seats are located in the front few rows and exit rows of the economy cabin on all aircraft and have additional pitch, complimentary alcoholic beverages and boarding one group ahead of the main cabin.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] It is available on all of the mainline fleet and American Eagle aircraft.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American also offers Basic Economy, the airline's lowest main cabin fare on many routes.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Basic Economy consists of a Main Cabin ticket with numerous restrictions, including waiting until check-in for a seat assignment, no upgrades or refunds, and boarding in the last group.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Originally Basic Economy passengers could only carry a personal item.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Later, American revised their Basic Economy policies to allow for a carry-on bag.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In May 2017, American announced it would add more seats to some of its Boeing 737 MAX 8 jets and reduce overall legroom in the basic economy class.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The last three rows were to lose 2 inches (5.1 cm), going from the current 31 to 29 inches (79 to 74 cm).
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The remainder of the main cabin was to have 30 inches (76 cm) of legroom.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This "Project Oasis" seating configuration has since been expanded to all 737 MAX 8s as well as standard Boeing 737-800 and non-transcontinental Airbus A321 jets.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] New Airbus A321neo jets have been delivered with the same configuration.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This configuration has been considered unpopular with passengers, especially American's frequent flyers, as the new seats have less padding, less legroom, and no seatback entertainment.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] AAdvantage is the frequent flyer program for American Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] It was launched on May 1, 1981, and remains the largest frequent flyer program, with over 115 million members as of 2021.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Miles accumulated in the program allow members to redeem tickets, upgrade service class, or obtain free or discounted car rentals, hotel stays, merchandise, or other products and services through partners.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] AAdvantage status corresponds with Oneworld status levels allowing elites to receive reciprocal benefits from American's Oneworld partner airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] AAdvantage co-branded credit cards are also available and offer other benefits.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Currently cards are issued by CitiCards, a subsidiary of Citigroup in the United States, by several banks including Butterfield Bank and Scotiabank in the Caribbean, and by Banco Santander in Brazil.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In December 2024, it was announced that American would be cutting ties with Barclays and would instead be rolling members into its partnership with Citigroup starting in 2026.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] AAdvantage allows one-way redemption, starting at 7,500 miles.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The Admirals Club was conceived by AA president C.R.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Smith as a marketing promotion shortly after he was made an honorary Texas Ranger.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Inspired by the Kentucky colonels and other honorary title designations, Smith decided to make particularly valued passengers "admirals" of the "Flagship fleet" (AA called its aircraft "Flagships" at the time).
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The list of admirals included many celebrities, politicians, and other VIPs, as well as more "ordinary" customers who had been particularly loyal to the airline.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] There was no physical Admirals Club until shortly after the opening of LaGuardia Airport, then known as New York Municipal Airport.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] During the airport's construction, New York Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia had an upper-level lounge for press conferences and business meetings.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] At one such press conference, he noted that the entire terminal was being offered for lease to airline tenants; after a reporter asked whether the lounge would be leased as well, LaGuardia replied that it would, and a vice president of AA immediately offered to lease the premises.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline then procured a liquor license and began operating the lounge as the "Admirals Club" in 1939.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The second Admirals Club opened at Washington National Airport.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Because it was illegal to sell alcohol in Virginia at the time, the club contained refrigerators for the use of its members so they could store their liquor at the airport.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] For many years, membership in the Admirals Club (and most other airline lounges) was by the airline's invitation.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] After a passenger sued for discrimination, the club switched to a paid membership program in 1974.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Though affiliated with the Admirals Club and staffed by many of the same employees, the Flagship Lounge is a separate lounge designed explicitly for customers flying in first class and business class on international flights and transcontinental domestic flights.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines, Inc., is publicly traded through its parent company, American Airlines Group Inc., under NASDAQ: AAL Nasdaq: AAL, with a market capitalization of about $11 billion as of 2024.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Eagle is a network of six regional carriers that operate under a codeshare and service agreement with American, operating flights to destinations in the United States, Canada, the Caribbean, and Mexico.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Three of these carriers are independent, and three are subsidiaries of American Airlines Group: Envoy Air Inc., Piedmont Airlines, Inc., and PSA Airlines Inc.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines is headquartered across several buildings in Fort Worth, Texas that it calls the "Robert L.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Crandall Campus" in honor of former president and CEO Robert Crandall.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The 1,700,000-square-foot (160,000 m2), five-building office complex was designed by Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The campus is located on 300 acres, adjacent to Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport, American's fortress hub.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Before it was headquartered in Texas, American Airlines was headquartered at 633 Third Avenue in the Murray Hill area of Midtown Manhattan, New York City.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1979, American moved its headquarters to a site at Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport, which affected up to 1,300 jobs.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Mayor of New York City Ed Koch described the move as a "betrayal" of New York City.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American moved to two leased office buildings in Grand Prairie, Texas.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline began leasing the facility from the airport, which owns the facility.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Following the merger of US Airways and American Airlines, the new company consolidated its corporate headquarters in Fort Worth, abandoning the US Airways headquarters in Phoenix, AZ.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of 2015, American Airlines is the corporation with the most significant presence in Fort Worth.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 2015, American announced it would build a new headquarters in Fort Worth.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Groundbreaking began in the spring of 2016, and occupancy was completed in September 2019.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline plans to house 5,000 new workers in the building.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] It will be located on a 41-acre (17 ha) property adjacent to the airline's flight academy and conference and training center, west of Texas State Highway 360, 2 miles (3.2 km) west from the current headquarters.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline will lease 300 acres (120 ha) from Dallas–Fort Worth International Airport, and this area will include the headquarters.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Construction of the new headquarters began after the demolition of the Sabre facility, previously on the site.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline considered developing a new headquarters in Irving, Texas, on the old Texas Stadium site, before deciding to keep the headquarters in Fort Worth.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1931, an American employee, Goodrich Murphy designed the AA logo as an entry in a logo contest.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The eagle in the logo was copied from a Scottish hotel brochure.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The initial logo contained large red letters on either side of the eagle, enclosed in a double red and white circle against a blue background.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This initial logo laid the foundation for the visual identity of the airline for 80 years.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The logo was modified for the first time in 1946, eliminating the red and white circles and making the eagle more prominent.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The corporate name was standardized in a sans-serif font in italic capital letters.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The visual identity was again updated in 1962 with the addition of a lighter red as an accent color and a medium grey replacing the grayish dark blue.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The logo was enclosed in a red circle, the eagle designed to be more figurative, and the double A's compacted.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1967 with the airline expanding its fleet and competing for new routes, a review of its visual identity was initiated. in 1968, under the direction of Massimo Vignelli (founding partner of Unimark) a new identity program was created.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] According to Vignelli, the approach was "not styling but reductionist based on the notion of timelessness." A blue stylized bird (created by Henry Dreyfuss) was placed between Unimark's AA symbols, a design which endured until 2013.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Thirty years later, in 1997, American Airlines was able to make its logo Internet-compatible by buying the domain AA.com.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] *AA* is also American's two-letter IATA airline designator.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On January 17, 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign with FutureBrand dubbed "A New American".
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This included a new logo, which includes elements of the 1967 logo.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines faced difficulty obtaining copyright registration for their 2013 logo.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On June 3, 2016, American Airlines sought to register it with the United States Copyright Office, but in October of that year, the Copyright Office ruled that the logo was ineligible for copyright protection, as it did not pass the threshold of originality, and was thus in the public domain.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American requested that the Copyright Office reconsider.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Still, on January 8, 2018, the Copyright Office affirmed its initial determination.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] After American Airlines submitted additional materials, the Copyright Office reversed its decision on December 7, 2018, and ruled that the logo contained enough creativity to merit copyright protection.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American's early liveries varied widely, but a standard livery was adopted in the 1930s, featuring an eagle painted on the fuselage.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The eagle became a symbol of the company and inspired the name of American Eagle Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Propeller aircraft featured an international orange lightning bolt running down the length of the fuselage, which was replaced by a simpler orange stripe with the introduction of jets.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In the late 1960s, American commissioned designer Massimo Vignelli to develop a new livery.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The original design called for a red, white, and blue stripe on the fuselage and a simple "AA" logo, without an eagle, on the tail; instead, Vignelli created a highly stylized eagle, which remained the company's logo until January 16, 2013.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On January 17, 2013, American unveiled a new livery.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Before then, American had been the only major U.S. airline to leave most of its aircraft surfaces unpainted.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Smith would not say he liked painted aircraft and refused to use any liveries that involved painting the entire plane.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Robert "Bob" Crandall later justified the distinctive natural metal finish by noting that less paint reduced the aircraft's weight, thus saving fuel costs.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In January 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign dubbed "The New American." In addition to a new logo, American Airlines introduced a new livery for its fleet.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline calls the new livery and branding "a clean and modern update".
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The current design features an abstract American flag on the tail, along with a silver-painted fuselage, as a throw-back to the old livery.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The new design was painted by Leading Edge Aviation Services in California.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Later in January 2013, Bloomberg asked the designer of the 1968 American Airlines logo (Massimo Vignelli) on his opinion over the rebranding.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Vignelli replied "now they have something other than Helvetica that's not as good or as powerful", adding that "it has no sense of permanence".
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In the end, American let their employees decide the new livery's fate.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On an internal website for employees, American posted two options, one the new livery and one a modified version of the old livery.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] All of the American Airlines Group employees (including US Airways and other affiliates) were able to vote.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American ultimately decided to keep the new look.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Parker announced that American would keep a US Airways and America West heritage aircraft in the fleet, with plans to add a heritage TWA aircraft and a heritage American plane with the old livery.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of September 2019, American has heritage aircraft for Piedmont, PSA, America West, US Airways, Reno Air, TWA, Allegheny, and AirCal in their fleet.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] They also have two AA branded heritage 737-800 aircraft, an AstroJet N905NN, and the polished aluminum livery used from 1967 to 2013, N921NN.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American, both before and after the merger with US Airways, has consistently performed poorly in rankings.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] *The Wall Street Journal'*s annual airline rankings have ranked American as the worst or second-worst U.S. carrier for ten of the past twelve years, and in the bottom three of U.S. airlines for at least the past twelve years.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The airline has persistently performed poorly in the areas of losing checked luggage and bumping passengers due to oversold flights.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In September 2024, the Association of Professional Flight Attendants ratified a five-year contract that included immediate wage increases of up to 20.5% and $514 million in retroactive pay, the first contract to include boarding pay for a unionized cabin crew in the United States.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In January 2025, the TWU-IAM alliance reached a two-year contract extension covering approximately 34,000 ground workers, with raises of 18 to 26 percent.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On February 9, 2026, the APFA board of directors issued a unanimous vote of no confidence in CEO Robert Isom, the first such action in the union's history.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1942, American Airlines established Sky Chefs, a wholly owned subsidiary, as a catering company to serve their fleet.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1986, Sky Chefs was sold to Toronto-based Onex Capital Corporation for $170 million.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Sky Chefs became a subsidiary of Onex Food Services Inc.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Since 2001, it has been fully owned by the LSG Group.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In the late-1960s, American Airlines established the Flagship Hotels chain as a subsidiary of Sky Chefs.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On July 21, 1972, American Airlines leased four hotels from the Loews Corporation, three of them branded as Americana Hotels, for a period of thirty years.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American merged the hotels with their Flagship Hotels, and rebranded the entire chain as Americana Hotels.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1980, American Airlines sold Americana Hotels to Bass Brothers Enterprises of Fort Worth, Texas.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Between October 1993 to July 1998, American Airlines was repeatedly cited for using high-sulfur fuel in motor vehicles at 10 major airports around the country, a violation of the Clean Air Act.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1981, as a means of creating revenue in a period of loss-making, American Airlines offered a lifetime pass of unlimited travel for the initial cost of $250,000.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] This entitled the pass holder to fly anywhere in the world without paying any subsequent fare.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] However, after some time, the airline realized they were making losses on the tickets, with the ticketholders costing them up to $1 million each.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Ticketholders were booking large numbers of flights with some ticketholders flying interstate for lunch or flying to London multiple times a month.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] AA raised the cost of the lifetime pass to $3 million, and then finally stopped offering it in 2003.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] AA then used litigation to cancel two of the lifetime offers, saying the passes "had been terminated due to fraudulent activity".
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] On October 24, 2017, the NAACP issued a travel advisory for American Airlines urging African Americans to "exercise caution" when traveling with the airline.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The NAACP issued the advisory after four incidents.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In one incident, a black woman was moved from first class to coach while her white traveling companion was allowed to remain in first class.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In another incident, a black man was forced to give up his seats after being confronted by two unruly white passengers.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] According to the NAACP, while they did receive complaints on other airlines, most of their complaints in the year before their advisory were on American Airlines.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In July 2018, the NAACP lifted their travel advisory saying that American has made improvements to mitigate discrimination and unsafe treatment of African Americans.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In October 2024, the United States Department of Transportation imposed a $50 million penalty on American Airlines for violations of federal disability protection laws between 2019 and 2023, the largest such penalty ever assessed against an airline.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The violations included unsafe physical assistance to wheelchair users and mishandling of thousands of wheelchairs.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Of the $50 million, half was payable to the U.S.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Treasury and half credited toward remediation investments including a wheelchair tracking system and additional staff at hub airports.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 1999, American Airlines sued Allied Pilots Association for $45.5 million over damages due to strike action, one of the largest fines ever levied against a trade union.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In January 2020, the Allied Pilots Association filed a lawsuit to stop flights between the United States and China over concerns about COVID-19.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The Association of Professional Flight Attendants supported the court action.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] At the time, COVID-19 was mostly contained to China and had not reached pandemic status yet.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Because of this action, American Airlines suspended their flights the following day.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] As of January 2025, American Airlines has had almost 60 aircraft hull losses, beginning with the crash of a Ford 5-AT-C Trimotor in August 1931.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Of the hull losses, most were propeller-driven aircraft, including three Lockheed L-188 Electra aircraft (of which one, the crash in 1959 of Flight 320, resulted in fatalities).
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The two accidents with the highest fatalities in both the airline's and U.S. aviation history were Flight 191 in 1979 and Flight 587 in 2001.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Out of the 17 hijackings of American Airlines flights, two aircraft were hijacked and destroyed in the September 11 attacks: Flight 11 crashed into the North Tower of the World Trade Center and Flight 77 crashed into the Pentagon.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Flight 11, which is responsible for an estimated 1,700 deaths, is the deadliest air crash in the history of aviation.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Two training flight accidents have occurred in which the crew was killed and six that resulted in no fatalities.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] Another four jet aircraft have been written off due to incidents while they were parked between flights or while undergoing maintenance.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines reported total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 20,092 Kt (-21,347 /-51.5% y-o-y).
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] The company aims to achieve net zero carbon emissions by 2050.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] American Airlines emitted roughly between 40,000,000-45,000,000 metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalents (MTCDE) annually between 2014-2019.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] In 2020, emissions declined to 20,000,000 MTCDE as a result of travel restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic, and have since increased back up to 40,000,000 MTCDE in 2023.
[src:dc-connector/american-airlines] According to Bloomberg terminal data, American Airlines receives an overall Environmental Social Governance (ESG) score of 5.82, which is ranked as a “leading” score compared to competitors in the industry.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The AWG originated in the number of drawing operations used to produce a given gauge of wire.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Very fine wire (for example, 30 gauge) required more passes through the drawing dies than 0 gauge wire did.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Manufacturers of wire formerly had proprietary wire gauge systems; the development of standardized wire gauges rationalized selection of wire for a particular purpose.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] While the AWG is essentially identical to the Brown & Sharpe (B&S) sheet metal gauge, the B&S gauge was designed for use with sheet metals.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] These are functionally interchangeable, but the use of B&S in relation to wire gauges, rather than sheet metal gauges, is technically improper.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Increasing gauge numbers denote logarithmically decreasing wire diameters, which is similar to many other non-metric gauging systems such as British Standard Wire Gauge (SWG).
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] However, AWG is dissimilar to IEC 60228, the metric wire-size standard used in most parts of the world, based directly on the wire cross-section area (in square millimetres, mm2).
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The AWG tables are for a single, solid and round conductor.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The AWG of a stranded wire is determined by the cross-sectional area of the equivalent solid conductor.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Because there are also small gaps between the strands, a stranded wire will always have a slightly larger overall diameter than a solid wire with the same AWG.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] By definition, 36 AWG is 0.005 inches in diameter, and 0000 AWG is 0.46 inches (11.68 mm) in diameter.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The ratio of these diameters is 1:92, and there are 40 gauge sizes from 36 to 0000, or 39 steps.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Because each successive gauge number increases cross sectional area by a constant multiple, diameters vary geometrically.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Any two successive gauges (e.g., *A* and *B*) have diameters whose ratio (dia.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Similarly for gauges *n* steps apart, the diameter ratio of the first to last gauges is about 1.1229*n*.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Where *n* is the AWG size for gauges from 36 to 0.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The standard ASTM B258-02 (2008), *Standard Specification for Standard Nominal Diameters and Cross-Sectional Areas of AWG Sizes of Solid Round Wires Used as Electrical Conductors*, defines the ratio between successive sizes to be the 39th root of 92, or approximately 1.1229.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] ASTM B258-02 also dictates that wire diameters should be tabulated with no more than 4 significant figures, with a resolution of no more than 0.0001 inches (0.1 mils) for wires thicker than 44 AWG, and 0.00001 inches (0.01 mils) for wires 45 AWG and thinner.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Sizes with multiple zeros are successively thicker than 0 AWG and can be denoted using "*number of zeros*/0", for example 4/0 AWG for 0000 AWG.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] For an m/0 AWG wire, use *n* = −(*m* − 1) = 1 − *m* in the above formulas.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The table below shows various data including both the resistance of the various wire gauges and the allowable current (ampacity) based on a copper conductor with plastic insulation.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The diameter information in the table applies to *solid* wires.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Stranded wires are calculated by calculating the equivalent cross sectional copper wire area.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Fusing current (melting wire) is estimated based on 25 °C (77 °F) ambient temperature.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The table below assumes DC, or AC frequencies equal to or less than 60 Hz, and does not take skin effect into account.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] "Turns of wire per unit length" refers to wire wound in a helix with the turns touching, as in a solenoid and is therefore the reciprocal of the conductor diameter.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] As wire in such a coil normally has insulation, this figure forms an upper bound.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] In the North American electrical industry, conductors thicker than 4/0 AWG are generally identified by the area in thousands of circular mils (kcmil), where 1 kcmil = 0.5067 mm2.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The next wire size thicker than 4/0 has a cross section of 250 kcmil.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] A *circular mil* is the area of a wire one mil in diameter.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] One million circular mils is the area of a circle with 1,000 mil (1 inch) diameter.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] An older abbreviation for one thousand circular mils is *MCM*.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] AWG can also be used to describe stranded wire.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The AWG size of a stranded wire represents the sum of the cross-sectional diameter of the individual strands; the gaps between strands are not counted.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] When made with circular strands, these gaps occupy about 25% of the wire area, thus requiring the overall bundle diameter to be about 13% larger than a solid wire of equal gauge.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Stranded wires are specified with three numbers, the overall AWG size, the number of strands, and the AWG size of a strand.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] The number of strands and the AWG size of a strand are separated by a slash.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] For example, a 22 AWG 7/30 stranded wire is a 22 AWG wire made from seven strands of 30 AWG wire.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] As indicated in the Formulae and Rules of thumb sections above, differences in AWG size translate directly into ratios of diameter or area.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] This property can be employed to easily find the AWG size of a stranded bundle by measuring the diameter and count of its strands.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] (This only applies to bundles with circular strands of identical size.) To find the AWG size of 7-strand wire with equal strands, subtract 8.4 from the AWG size of a strand.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Similarly, for 19-strand subtract 12.7, and for 37 subtract 15.6.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Measuring strand diameter is often easier and more accurate than attempting to measure bundle diameter and packing ratio.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Such measurement can be done with a wire gauge go-no-go tool or with a caliper or micrometer.
[src:dc-connector/american-wire-gauge] Alternative ways are commonly used in the electrical industry to specify wire sizes as AWG.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The **Anderson Powerpole** is a family of electrical connectors by Anderson Power Products (APP), although plug compatible connectors are now available from alternate sources.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Specific variants of this series of connectors have become de facto standards for conveying "higher power" direct current (DC) electrical power, although these standards are inconsistent and sometimes ignored.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Powerpole connectors are hermaphroditic, with "cis" connectivity (pin 1 on one connector mates with pin 1 on the other connector, and pin 2 with pin 2), thus avoiding the need to worry about which end is the plug and which the socket, or which end has the correct polarity.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] This is in contrast to the two-wire trailer plug, which has "trans" connectivity (pin 1 on each connector mates with pin 2 on the other).
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Powerpole connectors are available with current ratings of up to 180 amperes.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The 15/30/45 ampere-rated connectors are the most common, using the same plastic housing and differing only in the metal contact inserted into the housing.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The contact is selected based on the ampacity and wire gauge.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The colors can be used to signify signal types (power, speaker, logic, microphone audio, etc.) or differing voltages.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Powerpole connectors can be attached side to side and also stacked on top of each other to make, for example, four connections with one plug insertion.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The contacts are rated for 100,000 no-load insertions and 250 hot-plugs at full load.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] They range from 50 to 500 amps, 600 volts.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Some of Anderson's earlier patents have expired, thus other manufacturers have released plug-compatible connectors, such as "AMP Power Series" by Tyco / TE Connectivity, Sermos, and Lightspeed.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Powerpole connector was designed and patented by "Albert & J M Anderson Mfg Comp", then more recently by "Anderson Power Products".
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Many companies in the amateur astronomy space have adopted Powerpole connectors, as a large number of astronomical devices use 12-volts, and Powerpole connectors offer a low cost and easy solution to make adaptors, extensions, and distribution panels.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Powerpole connector has been adopted by many segments of the Amateur Radio (Ham Radio) community as their standard 12-volt DC power connector for everything from radios to DC power sources to accessories.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Three notable groups are the Amateur Radio Emergency Service (ARES), the Radio Amateur Civil Emergency Service (RACES) and the Wireless Institute Civil Emergency Network (WICEN).
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Standardization allows equipment owned by different hams to be used together without needing adapters in emergencies, at public service events, at field day, during contests, when borrowing equipment, etc.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Anderson Powerpole connector is more expensive than the older de facto standards of the two-wire trailer plug and the Molex connector, but provides a more reliable electrical connection (both mechanically and electrically), and is easier to adapt to a wider range of wire gauges.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Another advantage over the older trailer or Molex connectors is the Powerpole's superior ratings to withstand 100,000 no-load insertions and 250 hot-plugs at full load.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Many pieces of amateur radio equipment run on 12-volt DC automotive voltage, which is also called 13.8-volt DC.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The voltage delivered by a lead–acid battery with six-cells used as an automotive battery will vary depending on various electrical loads in a vehicle.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Without loads the battery will float from 11.7 to 12.8 volts, and while charging from an alternator the voltage will increase to 13.8–14.4 volts DC.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] For use in amateur radio, the community has adopted a standard color code, polarity, and specific physical arrangement for assembling pairs of Powerpole connectors.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The standard is red positive and black negative.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] When viewed from the contact side, a mnemonic for remembering the arrangement is: "Red [on] Right — Tongue [on] Top" (note the first letter alliteration).
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] West Mountain Radio, a major amateur radio supplier, has had a few 24 V DC products in their catalog for over a decade.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] They incorporate a 24 volt standard that has the orange body as +24 volts.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] An orange and black pair would be +24 volts on the orange and ground on the black.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] In model railways, the NTRAK Modular Railroading Society adopted the Powerpole PP30 connector as a recommend practice in 2005. and as a standard in 2011.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The use of the older Cinch-Jones connector has been deprecated, but is still permitted on legacy modules.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] However, the owner of a module with Cinch-Jones plugs is now required to provide adapter cables to the newer standard.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] North Raleigh Model Railroad Club (NRMRC) also uses Anderson Powerpole connectors.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Free-mo modular standard adopted Powerpole as the new connector standard as of 1 July 2015, with a one-year transition period to convert existing Jones connectors.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The connectors are used by some robot builders, including the FIRST Robotics Competition, MATE ROV Competition, and R2-D2 Builders Club.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Powerpole connectors are used by radio control (R/C) model hobbyist clubs.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] They may be known as "SB" connectors or "Sermos" connectors with the suppliers in that community.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Some buildings including data centers are increasingly designed for 380 V DC electric power distribution, as a way of improving electrical efficiency.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] DC power distribution has resulted in the need to standardize a Low Voltage (LV) connector with an integral ground conductor, which is safe for use by untrained personnel.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] The tendency of DC connectors to spark when disconnected from an inductive load requires the connector's insulating housing to contain the plasma arc, in addition to normal requirements such as preventing accidental finger contact.
[src:dc-connector/anderson-powerpole] Examples of such connectors are the Anderson Powerpole Pak connectors and the SDG (Saf-D-Grid) connector, designed with the form factor of an IEC C13 connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] A **DC connector** (or **DC plug**, for one common type) is an electrical connector that supplies direct current (DC) power.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Compared to domestic AC power plugs and sockets, DC connectors have many more standard types that are not interchangeable.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The dimensions and arrangement of DC connectors can be chosen to prevent accidental interconnection of incompatible sources and loads.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Types vary from small coaxial connectors used to power portable electronic devices from AC adapters to connectors used for automotive accessories and for battery packs in portable equipment.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These extra-low voltage connectors are rated at or below 120 VDC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Small cylindrical connectors come in various sizes.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These plugs are intended for use on the cable connected to an external AC adapter (power supply).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The matching jack or socket is permanently fitted to power the equipment.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Some of these jacks contain a normally closed contact, which can be used to disconnect internal batteries whenever the power supply is connected, avoiding the risk of battery leakage or explosion posed by incorrect battery recharging.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Cylindrical plugs usually have an insulated tip constructed to accept the insertion of a pin.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The outer body of the plug is one contact, most often but not always the negative side of the supply.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Inverted polarity plugs can and do damage circuitry when plugged in, even if the voltage is correct; not all equipment is equipped with protection.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] A pin mounted in the socket makes contact with a second internal contact.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The outer plug contact is often called the *barrel*, *sleeve*, or *ring*, while the inner is called the *tip*.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] There are a wide variety of sizes and designs for these power connectors, and many appear pretty similar to each other yet are not quite mechanically or electrically compatible.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In addition to many generic designs (whose original designer is unknown), there are at least two national standards—EIAJ in Japan and DIN in Germany, plus the JSBP connector used on some laptop computers.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The Japanese EIAJ standard includes five sizes, each supporting a specified range of voltages.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] However, most other coaxial DC power connectors have no specified voltage association.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Generic plugs are often named for the pin diameter they are designed to take.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Many non-proprietary co-axial power plugs are 5.5 mm (0.22 in) in outside diameter (OD) and 9.5 mm (0.37 in) in length.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Two pin sizes are standard in the jacks for this size plug body, 2.1 mm (0.083 in) and 2.5 mm (0.098 in), and the plugs should match.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] If the size is not known, it is difficult to distinguish by eye or measurement between the 2.1mm and 2.5mm ID plugs; some suppliers suggest simple methods.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Maximum current ratings commonly vary from unspecified up to 5 A (11 A for unique high-power versions from some companies), with 1 A, 2 A, and 5 A being common values.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The smaller types usually have lower ratings, both for current and voltage.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The 'tip' (i.e., the inner conductor) usually carries the positive (+) pole, but some devices and their power supplies use the negative tip.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The connector size does not usually indicate the voltage.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] It is not possible, except for some proprietary connectors, to reliably infer any information on power parameters (current, voltage, polarity, even whether AC or DC) by examining the connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Snap and lock DC power connectors look similar to Mini-DIN connectors but have either 3 or 4 thicker pins and a slightly larger mating shell.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Because of this, they do not mate with any of the standardized Mini-DIN connectors.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Some devices, however, use a proper 4-pin Mini-DIN connector for power instead, presenting the possibility of mating such a connector with the wrong port (such as an S-Video output).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Molex connectors were frequently used as DC power connectors in personal computers, for floppy, hard disk, and CD drives.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These connectors have four pins, +5 V (red), 2 common ground (black), and +12 V (yellow).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] SATA peripherals use a different style of connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Locking Molex connectors are available in 3, 4, and 6 terminal configurations.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Solder cup terminals are primarily designed for the in-line solder termination of conductors.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This style of terminal is principally designed as a precision-machined pin for insertion into connector bodies.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) has produced a standard for a system of 2-pin plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes in fixed and portable applications, either indoors or outdoors.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Safety extra-low voltage (SELV) plugs and socket-outlets carry up to 16 amperes, and have eight keying possibilities, to indicate 6, 12, 24, or 48 volts, AC or DC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The male shield has two keys projecting inwards, which fit into notches in the female body.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The larger key is at right angles to the pins, 2.0 ± 0.1 mm (0.079 ± 0.004 in) wide and ending at a radius of 4.9 ± 0.1 mm (0.193 ± 0.004 in) from the connector centre.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The angle of the second key from the first indicates the voltage and current type.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The eight permitted angles are multiples of 30° which are not multiples of 90°.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Angles of ±30° and ±60° indicate alternating current (50 or 60 Hz), while angles of ±120° or ±150° indicate direct current with the pin at 90° being negative and the pin at 270° being positive.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The second key is smaller than the first, 1.5 ± 0.1 mm (0.059 ± 0.004 in) wide ending at a radius of 6.4 ± 0.1 mm (0.252 ± 0.004 in) from the connector centre.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The corresponding notch in the female connector body is 1.8 ± 0.1 mm (0.071 ± 0.004 in) wide and ends at a radius of 6.2 ± 0.1 mm (0.244 ± 0.004 in) from the connector centre.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The so-called "Mini IEC connectors" are unrelated and not even standardized by the IEC at all; they are called that because they resemble a smaller IEC C13 connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) has standardized a set of multi-pin screw plugs matching ISO metric screw thread, available in M5, M8 and M12 sizes.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] M5 connectors are very low current, typically only used for signal wiring, while some M8 pin arrangements are rated for up to 3 A, and some M12 arrangements are available up to 16 A.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The multi-pin design caters for Ethernet, single and three-phase AC, as well as single or multiple voltage DC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The DC ratings are typically 60 V and below, however the F-coding is rated for 300 V (see #IEC 61076 (LV) below).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Tamiya connectors are commonly used on radio control (toy) vehicle battery packs and chargers.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The JST RCY-series connector is a 2.5mm-pitch and manufactured by J.S.T.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] It is known in radio control circles as the battery eliminator circuit (BEC) or P connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] JST also produces other types of connectors that are used in R/C and hobby electronics.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The Deans style T-Plug connector is a polarized high power plug that inhibits accidental reversed connections.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This also applies in particular to avoid the LiPo flash, which can cause burn injuries or related damage.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Depending on the make, Deans plugs are sensitive to overheating during soldering, as the plastic can become soft and the plug surfaces can easily twist.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Depending on the construction, they can support currents up to 40A (pulse to 70A).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Usual pin assignment T-Plug: negative (-) is the parallel pin; positive (+) is the perpendicular pin.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Inverter tabs/lugs are available in 2, 4, and 8 AWG.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These are designed to pass very high currents at voltages up to 600 V DC to and from battery packs, inverters, and other high-current loads to a terminal bus.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Two different airline in-seat power supply system (ISPSS) standards for DC power have been used in the past.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] American Airlines in the past used an automobile auxiliary power outlet.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Most other airlines that provide DC power use the smaller EmPower system, which has a 4-pin Hypertronics' D-series connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] It can supply 15 volts maximum 5 amperes.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Powerpole connectors are a series developed by Anderson Power Products[10] and available in a variety of sizes and colors.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The commonly used 15/30/45 series connectors are interoperable and use the same housings but different contacts for different wire sizes and current requirements.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Powerpole connectors are physically and electrically genderless, thus avoiding the need to worry about which end is the plug and which the socket, or which end has the correct polarity, as is the case with the physically but not electrically genderless two-wire trailer plug.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Powerpoles have been adopted as a standard 12 VDC connector by most RACES Radio Amateur Civil Emergency Service organizations and ARES Amateur Radio Emergency Service units.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] They deliver good current capability for their sizes and facilitate very easy pluggability for those without good eyesight or good lighting.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] However, they can be damaged relatively quickly and, if not correctly crimped, can occasionally separate from each other easily with minimal force unless additional retaining measures are taken.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The SAE connector is a physically self-mating hermaphrodite two-conductor DC connector commonly used for solar and automotive applications (including motorcycles).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] It is so named for the Society of Automotive Engineers which created the specifications this connector is based on.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Although the plug is physically hermaphroditic, and any SAE connector can be connected to any other SAE connector, they are NOT electrically hermaphroditic, and care needs to be taken to maintain correct polarity when connecting different plugs.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This connector typically applies a maintenance charge to a vehicle battery.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] When installed in a vehicle and attached to a battery, the polarity of the connector is always such that no short circuit will occur if the exposed terminal touches the vehicle chassis.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In most vehicles, this means that the exposed terminal connects to the battery's negative terminal.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Conversely, the positive terminal on a battery charger is exposed to mate with the concealed one on the vehicle side.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Although there is a risk of short-circuiting a battery charger, the risk is minimal and often mitigated by the circuitry of the battery charger itself.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] On the other hand, the short-circuit current of the lead–acid batteries installed in vehicles is sufficiently great that a short circuit could result in a fire or explosion.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The priority is therefore given to avoiding short circuits of the vehicle battery rather than the charger.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Although the term "SAE connector" is commonly used to refer to the pictured two-pin connector, many different connector standards are designated by SAE International which may also be referred to by this term.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Furthermore, while the design of the subject connector was inspired by and based on SAE Standards, the connector itself has no official SAE designation.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The SAE Specifications are available for J928 and J1239 but do require payment to be viewed.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The automobile auxiliary power outlet is also called a cigarette lighter receptacle, or cigar lighter receptacle, since it was originally designed as a lighter for cigars—hence its rather large size.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Nowadays, it is used to power automotive accessories such as portable inverters, mobile phone chargers and portable refrigerators.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These sockets were not originally designed to provide DC power, and are not an ideal DC connector for several reasons, but still widely used for compatibility to existing accessories.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Three sizes exist, one for 6 VDC and two for 12 VDC and the mating of the different sized 12 VDC plugs and jacks is problematic.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Because of this, and the small gauge wire sometimes used, they may provide unreliable power connections.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The polarity for 12 VDC sockets is center pin positive (+), outer collar negative (−).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Reversed polarity will damage some electronic devices.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Although the nominal voltage of a 12 V lead acid battery is 12 VDC, when the engine is running the car's battery charging system will bring the system voltage to 13.8 VDC or higher.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The possible range of battery voltages from 11–15 VDC must be taken into account by devices attached to the cigar lighter socket.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This connector is also often used for powering accessories on motorcycles, such as heated clothing (vests, gloves, etc.) or GPS units.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This makes "plugging in" easier to manage while wearing gloves.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] As the accessory lacks any power of its own, there's no risk of "shorting" the exposed connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Similar in concept to an automotive cigar lighter, the ISO 4165 connector is shorter and smaller.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Found most frequently on motorcycles, it is also known as a "BMW Accessory", "Hella", "Merit", "Norm" or "Powerlet" connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In the broadcast, film, and television industries, the 4-pin XLR connector is the standard for 12 V power.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The connectors are wired pin 1 negative, pin 4 positive.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Often pins 1 and 2 will be negative, 3 and 4 positive for a higher current rating.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Female connectors are used as supply and male connectors are used on loads.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Most battery belts and power supplies output 13.2 V, but equipment can usually handle a range of 11–18 volts to accommodate battery packs of varying voltages and charging while operating.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The readily available XLR3 is also used by some manufacturers as power supply plugs despite their being a well-accepted standard for other purposes.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In Australia, a T-configuration Clipsal socket is used for extra-low voltage DC power outlets, such as in stand-alone power systems (SAPS) or on boats, in order to prevent accidental connections of 12 V appliances into 240 V socket-outlets.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This connector is also used for temporary equipment in emergency vehicles.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The connector pins are mutually perpendicular, and are usually oriented to look like a capital T.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Polarity at the outlet can be random, and must be verified to avoid equipment damage.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Due to the popularity of USB for mobile phones and tablets, USB sockets and plugs have become a common choice for other small devices that require five volts or less, even those that require no data connection.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Examples include flashlights, toys such as small helicopters, and rechargeable battery packs (which in turn provide five volts over USB to recharge other devices).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Wall sockets with built-in USB power adapters and USB sockets are available.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In 2009, the EU created a common external power supply specification, a voluntary specification which encouraged mobile phone manufacturers to use the micro USB-B connector.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] As of 2016, most new mobile phones used this connector for charging.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In 2012, the USB Power Delivery (PD) specification was released.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The USB PD specification provides the ability for 5 V devices to draw more than (the USB battery-charging specification limit of) 7.5 W of power from USB "PD-aware" ports when using PD-aware USB cables.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The specification also allows USB PD ports to provide even greater power at higher voltages over PD-aware cables – up to 36 W at 12 V and 60 W at 20 V (for micro-USB connectors) and up to 60 W at 12 V and 100 W at 20 V (for standard USB A/B connectors).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] After previous connectors were deprecated in USB 3.2, the new USB-C plug has become a new standard for charging (and data transfer) over USB.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In the European Union, the Radio Equipment Directive 2021/0291, requires new smartphones to use USB-C as a universal charger by the end of 2024, and laptops by 2026.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These low voltage connectors are rated at or below 1,500 VDC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The Anderson SBS (commonly referred to as Anderson plug) and SBS Mini series of connectors are rated at up to 600 VDC at (depending on the connector) 50 A, 75 A or 110 A.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] They are only rated for disconnection under load at up to 120 VDC however.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These connectors see use in vehicle dual battery systems and higher power UPS systems, where the battery bank voltages are between 48 VDC and 500 VDC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] MC4 connectors are common on photovoltaic panels.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Because these panels are exposed to the weather for decades, MC4 includes a rubber sealing ring to keep out moisture.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Because solar panels are often stacked in strings of hundreds of volts, MC4 has locking clips to hold the wires together.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Because solar panels can be connected in series strings, or parallel arrays, the positive and negative terminals use separate connectors.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) has standardized a set of multi-pin screw plugs matching ISO metric screw thread, available in M5, M8 and M12 sizes (see #IEC 61076 (ELV) above).
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The *IEC TS 62735* standard specifies connectors capable of carrying between 294 and 400 VDC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] There are two connectors in the standard rated at 2.6 kW and 5.2 kW.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The lower current plug can be inserted into the higher current socket, but the higher current plug will not mate with the lower current socket.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The 2.6 kW plug can be disconnected under load, but the 5.2 kW plug cannot.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Designed primarily for supplying power to computer and communications equipment, these connectors are intended to allow data centers to migrate towards supplying equipment with DC power as an alternative to AC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The Saf-D-Grid connector delivers up to 600 VDC at up to 30 A, with the connector occupying the same space as an IEC 320 C13/C14 connector normally limited to 250 VAC at 10 A.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The connector can also be disconnected under load.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Like the IEC 62735, this connector was designed to replace the IEC connector used in computer power supplies so that they can be operated from 380–400 VDC instead.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] Introduced in January 2009, it arrived before the competing IEC standard, however despite this it has not seen widespread use.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The Imperium connector from Molex is aimed at automotive applications and is rated at 1,000 VDC at 250 A.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] As of 2021 the manufacturer has classed this connector as obsolete.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] In order to avoid heavy transformers onboard vehicles, high power charging of battery electric vehicles has the transformers in the ground station, and supply to the vehicle is done with DC at around 400 volts.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] These high voltage connectors are rated for voltages above 1,500 VDC.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The Banana connector, normally only rated for extra-low voltage, is available in a high voltage variant as well.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This version of the connector contains a thick shroud around both male and female connectors, permitting use at voltages of up to 30 kV.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] The shroud is typically deep enough to prevent connection by traditional banana plugs.
[src:dc-connector/dc-connector] This style of connector is often seen on high voltage test equipment, such as power supplies and volt meters capable of handling 10 kV and above.
